repository.corpname: Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library

did.abstract: The collection consists of reports, project documents, and technical drawings relating to water and sewage projects in California and Nevada, as well as other business and academic records documenting Roy Edwin Ramseier's career as a civil engineer between the 1950s and 1980s. Ramseier's papers document sanitation and water use in California and Nevada, particularly relating to suburbanization and small unincorporated communities. Ramseier also completed projects for private housing developments, government agencies, and businesses. The collection contains particularly thorough documentation of Beatty, Nevada and Valley Springs, California. There are also records relating to Squaw Valley, California, the site of the 1960 winter Olympics, where Ramseier worked on projects before and after the Olympic games.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: The materials are open for research.

acqinfo.p: Purchased from Marc Selvaggio, Bookseller on the Frederick W. and Carrie S. Beinecke Fund for Western Americana, 2016.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into four series: I. California Projects, 1926-1980. II. Nevada Projects, 1958-1978. III. Business Records and Academic Writings, 1912-1981. IV. Technical Drawings, 1935-1980.

bioghist.head: Roy Edwin Ramseier (1912-2010)
bioghist.p: Roy Edwin Ramseier (1912-2010) was a civil engineer who worked primarily on water and sewage projects in California and Nevada from the 1950s to 1980s. The son of a civil engineer, Ramseier studied engineering at the University of California, Berkeley. He established his business, Roy Edwin Ramseier and Associates, in Berkeley and remained in California for the entirety of his career. Ramseier also wrote several articles on air testing for sewers.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Roy Edwin Ramseier Papers. Yale Collection of Western Americana, Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Collections are processed to a variety of levels, depending on the work necessary to make them usable, their perceived research value, the availability of staff, competing priorities, and whether or not further accruals are expected. The library attempts to provide a basic level of preservation and access for all collections, and does more extensive processing of higher priority collections as time and resources permit. This collection received a basic level of processing, including rehousing and minimal organization, in 2017.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection consists of reports, project documents, and blueprints relating to water and sewage projects in California and Nevada, as well as other business and academic records documenting Roy Edwin Ramseier's career as a civil engineer between the 1950s and 1980s. Ramseier's papers document sanitation and water use in California and Nevada, particularly relating to suburbanization and small unincorporated communities. Ramseier also completed projects for private housing developments, government agencies, and businesses. The collection contains particularly thorough documentation of Beatty, Nevada and Valley Springs, California. There are also records relating to Squaw Valley, California, the site of the 1960 winter Olympics, where Ramseier worked on projects before and after the Olympic games.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: The Roy Edwin Ramseier Papers is the physical property of the Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University. Literary rights, including copyright, belong to the authors or their legal heirs and assigns. For further information, consult the appropriate curator.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged by project. Within each project, original order has been maintained.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The series comprises project documents, correspondence, and reports concerning Roy Edwin Ramseier's sewage and water projects in California. Ramseier's California clients included cities, planned communities, businesses, hospitals, and private residences. There is significant documentation of projects in Valley Springs, California. Other projects include Squaw Valley, California, the site of the 1960 winter Olympics.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The series comprises project documents, correspondence, and reports concerning Roy Edwin Ramseier's sewage and water projects in Nevada. Ramseier's Nevada clients were mostly cities and small towns, notably Beatty and Minden-Gardnerville. Other projects involved mines and ranches.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The series comprises the business records of Roy Edwin Ramseier and Associates and the academic records and writings of Roy Edwin Ramseier. Business records include invoices, tax records, and expense accounts. Academic records include Ramseier's academic writings about air testing for sewers and articles he collected about civil engineering, sewers, and water testing. Also included is a folder of the professional and personal records of Irvin B. Ramseier, Roy Edwin Ramseier's father, who was also a civil engineer.
